,Recommended,266130,24357479,"Posted: 16 July, 2016",all,Thaddeus J. Spider,"TL;DRI invited my brother to try this game out one time, and he got a perfect score on his first try.Me:  ""Wow, not bad.""Him:  ""I just did what they taught me to do in Infantry School.""So I guess the game works pretty well.On to the ReviewBreach & Clearis probably the most fun I've ever had playing a strategy game, largely because its plan-the-next-few-seconds approach both allows the player take his/her time while planning the next move and provides the satisfaction of seeing a successful plan play out in real-time.Level design is nicely varied while still generally keeping the unwritten rules of play applicable (i.e. the lessons learned from successful/unsuccessful runs of previous missions will be useful in later missions).  I never did figure out exactly what the game used (other than completion speed) to determine the 1-4 star performance rating, but I almost always agreed with the rating it gave me.I do wish that the game would allow the player to change the order in which their squad stacks up on doors, so that my medic wouldn't be taking point all the time while my direct-action guy sits in the back, but otherwisethe movement and control of squad members is well-thought-out and intuitive.There is a ludicrously elaborate equipment customization system that I appreciate, and I also like that it unlocks more weapons based on the total number of stars you've acquired as mission ratings.  However, the number of stars required to unlock the guns, as well as the amount of money awarded for missions versus the amount that guns cost, is a bit unreasonable.  Even getting maximum ratings on all of the missions requires several runs through all of the missions in order to have enough stars to unlock the top-tier weapons, and even more runs to get the money to purchase them.  But again, this is a relatively minor complaint, and on the whole the system works well.In short, while it isn't perfect,Breach & Clearis a solid tactical strategy game with sound core mechanics and enough variety to keep it interesting.  Highly recommended."
