,Recommended,266130,13230951,"Posted: 4 December, 2014",all,GhostSmooch,"N.B. my recommendation for this game depends entirely on the the fact that I picked it up for 4$. If I had paid full price for this game, I would probably feel a little more lukewarm about this. Now that that's out of the way...This game really shines in its mechanics. There is a strong incentive to be careful, plan ahead, and make the right choices in terms of tactics and equipment. Moreover, there are multiple paths to success, and the variety of maps makes it difficult to confine yourself to a single strategy.As compared to other turn-based tactical games (I'm thinking X-Com: EU in particular), the action plays out in a very satisfying way. Simultaneous movement of your troops and enemies adds a lot of realism to the game. The ability to choose firing angles along your path, rather than picking targets with hit percentages, really gives you the sense that you're in control, not the RNG. The cover system is excellent, with flanking angles being the default rather than an option. Stealth is a viable option with suppressors and a welcome addition to the game.Unfortunately, this game does have some issues. Most glaring, and something that puts a bit of a damper on the strength of the gameplay, is that the AI isverybad at adapting to you. I've often seen the AI deliberately take a flanked position en lieu of something which offered full protection. Higher difficulties do not seem to increase intelligence but buff enemies. Alert states seem a bit off, since enemies only really react to seeing you, instead of, say, being alerted when the person in front of them is dropped by a gun with a silencer on it.The most glaring flaw of this game is customization and the menu system. For a game whose selling point is massive customization, the system feels far more shallow once you actually delve into it. There are clear winners in attachments and upgrades, so you end up sticking to those when you can afford them. The menu system for upgrades is by far the worst feature of this game. Having to unequip each upgrade and then confirm the unequip so that you can switch weapons and put those upgrades back on is clunky and slow. Doing it once is bad, doing it for each of your four soldiers (and then back again after a mission) is torturous. In addition, the cosmetic features of your soldiers reduce to face gear and camo patterns. X-Com may not have the depth of this game's tactical play, but I felt way more invested in my individual troops in that game.Aesthetically speaking, the game isn't much to look at. The graphics are sloppy, but since you're spending so much time zoomed out, it hardly matters. What you see conveys what you need to know, and that's fine. Less fine are the sounds. I get that they're sticking to realism, but none of the sound FX seem to have the necessary 'weight', if that makes sense.TL;DR if this game is on sale and you need a quick fix for realistic tactical combat, this is a game for you. It's loads of fun for a little while and outshines its contemporaries in its mechanics. There are some areas that seriously require polishing, but if you can overlook those, you'll have a ball."
,Recommended,266130,13244536,"Posted: 5 December, 2014",all,The kid that everyone hates,"picked this game up on a sale for £2.74 and i have to say it is a great game, simple controls make it more of a casual simulator but the AI could be a little harder 8/10"
,Recommended,266130,13259912,"Posted: 6 December, 2014",all,Necessary Gassing,"I bought this game during the black weekend sale and bought it just for another game to play for a bit and didn't expect to enjoy it this much 13.7 hours in 3-4 days is quite alot for me and I still love. theres quite a few upgrades, quite a few ways to customize your characters differently I just wish there where more missions :/"
,Recommended,266130,13265493,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,Flying Shisno,"This is a great Squad Tactics, turn based strategy. When you load up a game, it'll ask you to make a Squad. First you choose what kind of Special Forces you want your dudes to be: US Navy Seals, Germany's KSK, Canada’s JTF2, UK's SAS, and if you get the DLC, you can play as the Green Frozen Synapse guys too. After that, you choose each one of your 4 guys portrait/face, which is pretty limited, and their class, such as weapon expert, medic, direct assault, etc., which governs what kind of skills you can use in game and what kind of passives they have. You can name your squad too.Once you're in the game, you have your squad move through the level eliminating terrorists. If you've ever played Frozen Synapse, moving around and killing is like that, but less in-depth. Click where you want to move, and where you want him to face when he get's there. You can click along his path and have him look in a different direction when he get's there. You can also have them throw grenades and other equipment if you've purchased them(more on this in a bit). You do this with all 4 squad members, click 'breach', which starts the turn, and they'll all do their orders immediately, shooting at enemies that enter their line of site. A 'turn' is pretty much 5 seconds, and clicking Breach will have them carry out orders and shoot people for 5 seconds before time stops and you can issue another set of orders Some have skills and passives, like the Weapons Expert has 'Suppressive Fire', which does what it says. The Intelligence class can see all around them, a 360° range of vision for a fairly short distance, about 5 feet. Normally, a soldier has  the standard 40°-45° cone line of sight in front of them(no distance restrictions), simulating a person's eyesight. The Intelligence class has this stanard 45° cone, plus a much smaller 360° view, which extends maybe 10-ish feet. This is great for when an enemy is in a place you didn't expect. Normally a soldier will turn around by himself and shoot back at an enemy that shot him, but that's a precious few seconds of getting wailed on. The 360° view let's the Intelligence class immediately start to turn around the second he enters his range. You'll still get hit since you'll still have to turn around, but the chance of dying has been drastically lowered.After each mission you get money, experience, and a 1-4 Star rating depending on how well you did,  Experience will level up a soldier, and when he levels, you can put 5 points into one of their stats. Each class has some stats all on their own, like the Intelligence Class has a stat that increases his 360° view distance. All Classes have some similar stats though, like all have a 'Moving Speed(distance you can travel in one turn). 'Accuracy', 'Health', and 'Reaction', which is how long it takes for them to 'lock on' to the enemy and start shooting. All stats can be increased to 100, and each stat starts at around 45-55. The type of squad, such as US Seals/German KSK/UK SAS/etc, plays in here too. Each type has a beginning bonus to one of their stats. I believe either the US Rangers or Seals starts with their Accuracy at 75. Each squad type has a bonus, and that bonus can pretty much aid in your preferred play style.As for money, You get a $200-ish bonus for completing a mission for the first time, and I think $200 per Star(rating), at least on normal difficulty(4 modes). There are other bonuses and penalties that reward/subtract too. Anyway, in the main menu there's a Marketplace, where you can buy new clothes, armor, helmets, weapons, all sorts of weapon attachments, and consumable items. Most of these items will offer some sort stat boost, like scopes increasing accuracy and armor(vests) increasing health. This isn't Door Kickers btw, where buying the gun once unlocks it for free use with everyone else. If you want your 4 squad members to wield that shiny rifle, then you'll need to buy that shiny rifle 4 times. I wasn't  mocking Door Kickers btw. I love that game too. If you're short on cash, and there's a particular level you like, you can simply do that level a few times to earn money. Just keep in mind that you'll only really earn money for the amount of stars you get on that run(4 max). So at most, on normal difficulty at least, you can only get $800 max, and you'll probably have some of that subtracted due to taking damage or taking too long. The prices are not ridiculous btw. They're not expensive, but you won't be buying everything in the first hour(or week).There are a good number of missions to do, and lots of gear and weapons to get and play around with. I definitely recommend this game."
